3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC, based on the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices. Long positions pay short positions when funding is positive (perpetual trades above spot), while shorts pay longs when negative. The zero maker fee structure on MEXC significantly reduces the cost basis for arbitrage strategies, though the 0.03% taker fee applies to market orders. Funding payments occur automatically for positions held during the funding timestamp."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ETH","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETH/USDT on MEXC presents compelling arbitrage potential due to Ethereum's high volatility and the pair's substantial trading volume. The zero maker fees allow arbitrageurs to establish hedged positions cost-effectively, while the 8-hour funding intervals provide multiple opportunities daily to capture rate differentials."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETH/USDT funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% per 8-hour period, with pronounced spikes during major market moves. During bull runs, positive funding rates often persist for weeks as long positions dominate, creating consistent income opportunities for short hedgers. Bear markets frequently produce negative rates as shorts pile in, benefiting long position holders. The pair exhibits higher volatility in funding rates compared to BTC/USDT, particularly around Ethereum network upgrades and DeFi market developments. Weekend periods often show reduced funding rate volatility due to lower institutional participation."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fee structure creates optimal conditions for delta-neutral arbitrage between perpetual and spot markets. Traders can establish long perpetual/short spot positions when funding rates are consistently negative, collecting payments while maintaining market neutrality. The exchange's aggressive token listing strategy means ETH/USDT often experiences unique funding dynamics not seen on other platforms. Position sizing should account for MEXC's sometimes thinner order books compared to tier-1 exchanges, though this also creates opportunities for better execution during low-volume periods. The 8-hour funding cycle allows for tactical position adjustments between payments."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's regulatory uncertainty and questionable volume reporting practices require enhanced due diligence for funding rate arbitrage strategies. Counterparty risk considerations include potential withdrawal restrictions during market stress and the exchange's relatively recent establishment in global markets. Order book depth can vary significantly during volatile periods, potentially impacting large position liquidations or adjustments. The high leverage options (up to 125x) amplify both profit potential and liquidation risks, requiring careful margin management. Funding rate arbitrageurs should monitor MEXC's operational status closely and maintain diversified exchange exposure to mitigate platform-specific risks."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes MEXC's ETH/USDT funding rates different from other exchanges?","answer":"MEXC's zero maker fee structure and 8-hour funding cycles create unique arbitrage dynamics. The exchange's aggressive listing strategy and growing Asian user base often result in funding patterns that diverge from established exchanges like Binance or Bybit."},{"question":"How do MEXC's thin order books affect funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"Thinner order books can create both opportunities and risks. While they may offer better execution for smaller positions during quiet periods, large arbitrage positions might face slippage challenges. The zero maker fees help offset some liquidity concerns for patient order placement."},{"question":"Are there withdrawal or operational risks specific to MEXC for arbitrage?","answer":"MEXC's limited regulatory compliance and recent regulatory scrutiny in some jurisdictions create operational risks. Arbitrageurs should maintain smaller position sizes relative to tier-1 exchanges and ensure they have alternative platforms available. The exchange has faced periodic withdrawal delays during high volatility."},{"question":"What's the optimal position size for ETH/USDT funding arbitrage on MEXC?","answer":"Given MEXC's order book depth limitations, positions above $100,000 may face execution challenges. The zero maker fees make smaller, more frequent trades viable. Conservative sizing at 2-5% of typical daily volume helps ensure smooth entry and exit execution."}]}]
